# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: genetic-code
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] The relative positions of structures along strands of nucleic acid, including genes and various protein binding sites, are usually noted as being either *upstream* (towards the 5′-end) or *downstream* (towards the 3′-end).
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] Directionality is related to, but different from, sense.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] Transcription of single-stranded RNA from a double-stranded DNA template requires the selection of one strand of the DNA template as the template strand that directly interacts with the nascent RNA due to complementary sequence.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] The other strand is not copied directly, but necessarily its sequence will be similar to that of the RNA.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] Transcription initiation sites generally occur on both strands of an organism's DNA, and specify the location, direction, and circumstances under which transcription will occur.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] If the transcript encodes one or (rarely) more proteins, translation of each protein by the ribosome will proceed in a 5′-to-3′ direction, and will extend the protein from its N-terminus toward its C-terminus.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] For example, in a typical gene a start codon (5′-ATG-3′) is a DNA sequence within the sense strand.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] Transcription begins at an upstream site (relative to the sense strand), and as it proceeds through the region it copies the 3′-TAC-5′ from the template strand to produce 5′-AUG-3′ within a messenger RNA (mRNA).
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] The mRNA is scanned by the ribosome from the 5′ end, where the start codon directs the incorporation of a methionine (bacteria, mitochondria, and plastids use *N*-formylmethionine instead) at the N terminus of the protein.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] By convention, single strands of DNA and RNA sequences are written in a 5′-to-3′ direction except as needed to illustrate the pattern of base pairing.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] The 5′-end (pronounced "five prime end") designates the end of the DNA or RNA strand that has the fifth carbon in the sugar-ring of the deoxyribose or ribose at its terminus.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] A phosphate group attached to the 5′-end permits ligation of two nucleotides, i.e., the covalent binding of a 5′-phosphate to the 3′-hydroxyl group of another nucleotide, to form a phosphodiester bond.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] Removal of the 5′-phosphate prevents ligation.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] To prevent unwanted nucleic acid ligation (e.g. self-ligation of a plasmid vector in DNA cloning), molecular biologists commonly remove the 5′-phosphate with a phosphatase.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] The 5′-end of nascent messenger RNA is the site at which post-transcriptional capping occurs, a process which is vital to producing mature messenger RNA.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] Capping increases the stability of the messenger RNA while it undergoes translation, providing resistance to the degradative effects of exonucleases.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] It consists of a methylated nucleotide (methylguanosine) attached to the messenger RNA in a rare 5′- to 5′-triphosphate linkage.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] The 5′-*flanking* region of a gene often denotes a region of DNA which is not transcribed into RNA.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] The 5′-flanking region contains the gene promoter, and may also contain enhancers or other protein binding sites.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] The 5′-*untranslated* region (5′-UTR) is a region of a gene which is transcribed into mRNA, and is located at the 5′-end of the mRNA.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] This region of an mRNA may or may not be translated, but is usually involved in the regulation of translation.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] The 5′-untranslated region is the portion of the DNA starting from the cap site and extending to the base just before the AUG translation initiation codon of the main coding sequence.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] This region may have sequences, such as the ribosome binding site and Kozak sequence, which determine the translation efficiency of the mRNA, or which may affect the stability of the mRNA.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] The 3′-end (three prime end) of a strand is so named due to it terminating at the hydroxyl group of the third carbon in the sugar-ring, and is known as the *tail end*.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] The 3′-hydroxyl is necessary in the synthesis of new nucleic acid molecules as it is ligated (joined) to the 5′-phosphate of a separate nucleotide, allowing the formation of strands of linked nucleotides.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] Molecular biologists can use nucleotides that lack a 3′-hydroxyl (dideoxyribonucleotides) to interrupt the replication of DNA.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] This technique is known as the dideoxy chain-termination method or the Sanger method, and is used to determine the order of nucleotides in DNA.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] The 3′-end of nascent messenger RNA is the site of post-transcriptional polyadenylation, which attaches a chain of 50 to 250 adenosine residues to produce mature messenger RNA.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] This chain helps in determining how long the messenger RNA lasts in the cell, influencing how much protein is produced from it.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] The 3′-*flanking* region is a region of DNA that is not copied into the mature mRNA, but which is present adjacent to 3′-end of the gene.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] It was originally thought that the 3′-flanking DNA was not transcribed at all, but it was discovered to be transcribed into RNA and quickly removed during processing of the primary transcript to form the mature mRNA.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] The 3′-flanking region often contains sequences that affect the formation of the 3′-end of the message.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] It may also contain enhancers or other sites to which proteins may bind.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] The 3′-*untranslated* region (3′-UTR) is a region of the DNA which *is* transcribed into mRNA and becomes the 3′-end of the message, but which does not contain protein coding sequence.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] Everything between the stop codon and the polyA tail is considered to be 3′-untranslated.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] The 3′-untranslated region may affect the translation efficiency of the mRNA or the stability of the mRNA.
[src:genetic-code/5-to-3] It also has sequences which are required for the addition of the poly(A) tail to the message, including the hexanucleotide AAUAAA.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] The **adaptor hypothesis** is a theoretical scheme in molecular biology to explain how information encoded in the nucleic acid sequences of messenger RNA (mRNA) is used to specify the amino acids that make up proteins during the process of translation.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] It was formulated by Francis Crick in 1955 in an informal publication of the RNA Tie Club, and later elaborated in 1957 along with the central dogma of molecular biology and the sequence hypothesis.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] It was formally published as an article "On protein synthesis" in 1958.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] The name "adaptor hypothesis" was given by Sydney Brenner.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] Crick postulated that there must exist a small molecule to precisely recognise and bind the mRNA sequences while amino acids are being synthesised.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] The hypothetical adaptor molecule was later established to be a hitherto unknown nucleic acid, transfer RNA (tRNA).
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] In 1953, English biophysicist Francis Crick and American biologist James Watson, working together at the Cavendish Laboratory of the University of Cambridge, worked out the correct description of the structure of DNA, one of the major genetic materials.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] In their follow-up paper the same year, they introduced the concept of genetic information alongside the notion that DNA and protein cloud be related.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] By 1954, it was becoming to be understood that DNA, RNA (only messenger RNA was understood at the time, but only as a vague nucleic acid, and identified as such only in 1960) and proteins were related as components of the same genetic information pathway.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] However, the structure of RNA and details of how these biological molecules related and interact with each other were still a mystery, especially on how proteins could be synthesised from nucleic acids.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] Watson called this problem "the mysteries of life" in his letter to Crick.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] Evidences had been accumulating since the 1940s that protein synthesis occurs simultaneously with increased level of RNA in the cytoplasm.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] The relationship between DNA and RNA for protein synthesis was first hypothesised by French biologist André Boivin and Roger Vendrely in 1947.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] They wrote in *Experientia* (later renamed *Cellular and Molecular Life Sciences*): "Through catalytic actions the macromolecular desoxyribonucleic acids govern the building of macromolecular ribonucleic acids, and, in turn, these control the production of cytoplasmic enzymes.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] In truth, the enzymic equipment results simultaneously from the effect of ribonucleic acids (catalytic action) and from the effect of substrates (mass action).
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] Alexander Dounce, of the University of Rochester Medical Center in New York, came close to the correct interpretation of protein synthesis from RNA.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] In 1952, he proposed the first notion, naming it the "nucleic acid template hypotheses," that proteins were made from RNA, rather than from DNA.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] Soviet-American physicist George Gamow was the first to come up with a coherent scheme for protein synthesis from DNA.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] Based on the Watson-Crick model, he envisaged that the DNA itself is a direct template for protein synthesis.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] Assuming that the four bases of DNA could produce 20 different combinations as triplets, he suggested that the different amino acids must correspond to a twenty-letter alphabet of the nucleotide sequence.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] In such configuration, the DNA directly produces proteins from the free molecules of amino acids.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] Watson, then at the California Institute of Technology in Massachusetts, also thought up the issue.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] Unlike Gamow, he realised the possible importance of RNA as an intermediate stage in protein synthesis.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] He initially imagined that DNA was first converted by chemical reaction to RNA, but then changed his view to DNA as a template for RNA synthesis.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] This latter model, which he called "not ugly" was starting to become more convincing.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] To solve the riddle of protein synthesis, Gamow (as the Synthesiser) created an informal team of scientists which he called the RNA Tide Club in 1954.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] As his prediction to denote 20 amino acids, the club could have only 20 members, with the designated officers: Crick (as the Pessimist), Rich (the Lord Privy Seal) and Watson (the Optimist) among them.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] Coming across Gamow's paper, Crick immediately noticed some issues in the scheme.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] The first was that he and Watson never had before counted the 20 amino acids or the possible 20 nucleotide triplets (although Gamow was subsequently proven to be correct and his model was the first prediction of the genetic code).
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] The other issue was that RNA and protein synthesis appeared to exclusively take place in the cytoplasm, and not in the nucleus, indicating that DNA to protein pathway requires just not direct chemical binding, but some kind of mediator must be involved.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] Crick began to think of a solution to this problem in the line of Watson's idea that the role of RNA was overlooked.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] He rejected Gamow's assumption that molecules like amino acids that are too different chemically from nucleic acid that it would be structurally impossible to bind to DNA.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] Instead, he visualised a certain kind but unknown molecule that linked nucleic acids and carry amino acids to ribosomes to form peptide chains.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] As he discussed it with his colleague Sydney Brenner about the features of such molecule, Brenner was impressed with the idea and named the concept as the "adaptor hypothesis".
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] The adaptor was then a hypothetical molecule that apparently help in an indirect interaction between DNA, RNA and amino acids during protein synthesis.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] Crick admitted that he had no way knowing what kind of chemical substance was an adaptor, but then prudently suggested that it was composed of nucleotides, a sort of RNA, that had common features of both DNA and RNA.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] He even speculated that "insulin, for example, are probably RNA-made proteins.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] Perhaps a special class of DNA-made proteins exists, almost always in small quantities (and thus normally overlooked).
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] The adaptor hypothesis was fully formalised in 1957.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] Crick presented the elaborate explanation in a lecture titled "Protein synthesis" on 19 September 1957 at the Society for Experimental Biology symposium on the Biological Replication of Macromolecules, held at University College London.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] The adaptor hypothesis was framed to explain how information could be extracted from a nucleic acid and used to put together a string of amino acids in a specific sequence, that sequence being determined by the nucleotide sequence of the nucleic acid (DNA or RNA) template.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] Crick proposed that each amino acid is first attached to its own specific "adaptor" piece of nucleic acid (in an enzyme-catalysed reaction).
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] The order of assembly of the amino acids is then determined by a specific recognition between the adaptor and the nucleic acid which is serving as the informational template.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] In this way the amino acids could be lined up by the template in a specific order.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] Coupling between adjacent amino acids would then lead to the synthesis of a polypeptide whose sequence is determined by the template nucleic acid.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] Crick's thinking behind this proposal was based on a general consideration of the chemical properties of the two classes of molecule — nucleic acids and proteins.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] The amino acids are characterised by having a variety of side chains which vary from being hydrophilic to hydrophobic: their individual characters reside in the very different properties these side chains have.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] By contrast, a nucleic acid is composed of a string of nucleotides whose sequence presents a geometrically defined surface for hydrogen bonding.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] This makes nucleic acids good at recognising each other, but poor at distinguishing the varied side chains of amino acids.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] Although his concept about the direct synthesis of amino acid from the DNA double strands was proven false, his prediction on the nature of amino acids and how they were coded by the DNA sequences (triplet nucleotides) were confirmed the key components of protein synthesis.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] This broad concept is now known as the genetic code.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] As Crick was lecturing on his hypothesis, such adaptors do exist in nature was already discovered by the team of Mahlon Hoagland and Paul Zamecnik, whose paper was published the following year in March 1958.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] These "soluble RNAs" are now called transfer RNAs and mediate the translation of messenger RNAs on ribosomes according to the rules contained in the genetic code.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] Crick imagined that his adaptors would be small, perhaps 5-10 nucleotides long.
[src:genetic-code/adaptor-hypothesis] In fact, they are much larger, having a more complex role to play in protein synthesis, and are closer to 100 nucleotides in length.
[src:genetic-code/adenine] Adenine has a central role in cellular respiration.
[src:genetic-code/adenine] It is part of adenosine triphosphate which provides the energy that drives and supports most activities in living cells, such as protein synthesis, muscle contraction, and nerve impulse propagation.
[src:genetic-code/adenine] In respiration it also participates as part of the cofactors nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide, flavin adenine dinucleotide, and coenzyme A.
[src:genetic-code/adenine] It is also part of adenosine, adenosine monophosphate, cyclic adenosine monophosphate, adenosine diphosphate, and S-adenosylmethionine.
[src:genetic-code/adenine] Adenine forms several tautomers, compounds that can be rapidly interconverted and are often considered equivalent.
[src:genetic-code/adenine] However, in isolated conditions, i.e. in an inert gas matrix and in the gas phase, mainly the 9H-adenine tautomer is found.
[src:genetic-code/adenine] Purine metabolism involves the formation of adenine and guanine.
[src:genetic-code/adenine] Both adenine and guanine are derived from the nucleotide inosine monophosphate (IMP), which in turn is synthesized from a pre-existing ribose phosphate through a complex pathway using atoms from the amino acids glycine, glutamine, and aspartic acid, as well as the coenzyme tetrahydrofolate.
[src:genetic-code/adenine] Patented August 20, 1968, the current recognized method of industrial-scale production of adenine involves heating formamide under 120 °C.
[src:genetic-code/adenine] Adenine is one of the two purine nucleobases (the other being guanine) used in forming nucleotides of the nucleic acids.
[src:genetic-code/adenine] In DNA, adenine binds to thymine via two hydrogen bonds to assist in stabilizing the nucleic acid structures.
[src:genetic-code/adenine] In RNA, which is used for protein synthesis, adenine binds to uracil.
[src:genetic-code/adenine] Adenine forms adenosine, a nucleoside, when attached to ribose, and deoxyadenosine when attached to deoxyribose.
[src:genetic-code/adenine] It forms adenosine triphosphate (ATP), a nucleoside triphosphate, when three phosphate groups are added to adenosine.
[src:genetic-code/adenine] Adenosine triphosphate is used in cellular metabolism as one of the basic methods of transferring chemical energy between chemical reactions.
[src:genetic-code/adenine] ATP is thus a derivative of adenine, adenosine, cyclic adenosine monophosphate, and adenosine diphosphate.
[src:genetic-code/adenine] In older literature, adenine was sometimes called **Vitamin B4**, but is no longer considered a vitamin.
[src:genetic-code/adenine] Due to it being synthesized by the body and not essential to be obtained by diet, it does not meet the definition of vitamin and is no longer part of the Vitamin B complex.
[src:genetic-code/adenine] However, two B vitamins, niacin and riboflavin, bind with adenine to form the essential cofactors nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD) and flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD), respectively.
[src:genetic-code/adenine] Hermann Emil Fischer was one of the early scientists to study adenine.
[src:genetic-code/adenine] It was named in 1885 by Albrecht Kossel after Greek *ἀδήν* aden "gland", in reference to the pancreas, from which Kossel's sample had been extracted.
[src:genetic-code/adenine] Adenine can be prepared from ammonia and hydrogen cyanide (HCN) in aqueous solution, a process that has implications for the origin of life on Earth.
[src:genetic-code/adenine] On August 8, 2011, a report, based on NASA studies with meteorites found on Earth, was published suggesting building blocks of DNA and RNA (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) may have been formed extraterrestrially in outer space.
[src:genetic-code/alanine] Under biological conditions, alanine exists in its zwitterionic form with its amine group protonated (as −NH+3) and its carboxyl group deprotonated (as −CO−2).
[src:genetic-code/alanine] Alanine is encoded by all codons starting with GC (GCU, GCC, GCA, and GCG).
[src:genetic-code/alanine] The L-isomer of alanine (left-handed) is the one that is incorporated into proteins.
[src:genetic-code/alanine] L-alanine is second only to L-leucine in rate of occurrence, accounting for 7.8% of the primary structure in a sample of 1,150 proteins.
[src:genetic-code/alanine] The right-handed form, D-alanine, occurs in peptides in some bacterial cell walls (in peptidoglycan) and in some peptide antibiotics, and occurs in the tissues of many crustaceans and molluscs as an osmolyte.
[src:genetic-code/alanine] Alanine is not an essential amino acid in humans because it can be synthesized metabolically and does not need to be present in the diet.
[src:genetic-code/alanine] However hypoalaninemia (alanine deficiency) is possible under certain conditions such as ketotic hypoglycemia.
[src:genetic-code/alanine] Alanine was first synthesized in 1850 when Adolph Strecker combined acetaldehyde and ammonia with hydrogen cyanide.
[src:genetic-code/alanine] The amino acid was named *Alanin* in German, in reference to aldehyde, with the interfix *-an-* for ease of pronunciation, the German ending *-in* used in chemical compounds being analogous to English *-ine*.
[src:genetic-code/alanine] Alanine is an aliphatic amino acid, because the side-chain connected to the α-carbon atom is a methyl group (-CH3).
[src:genetic-code/alanine] Alanine is the simplest α-amino acid after glycine.
[src:genetic-code/alanine] The methyl side-chain of alanine is non-reactive and is therefore hardly ever directly involved in protein function.
[src:genetic-code/alanine] Alanine is a nonessential amino acid, meaning it can be manufactured by the human body, and does not need to be obtained through the diet.
[src:genetic-code/alanine] Alanine is found in a wide variety of foods, but is particularly concentrated in meats.
[src:genetic-code/aliphatic-compound] In organic chemistry, hydrocarbons (compounds composed solely of carbon and hydrogen) are divided into two classes: aromatic compounds and **aliphatic compounds** (/ˌælɪˈfætɪk/; G.
[src:genetic-code/aliphatic-compound] Aliphatic compounds can be saturated (in which all the C-C bonds are single, requiring the structure to be completed, or 'saturated', by hydrogen) like hexane, or unsaturated, like hexene and hexyne.
[src:genetic-code/aliphatic-compound] Open-chain compounds, whether straight or branched, and which contain no rings of any type, are always aliphatic.
[src:genetic-code/aliphatic-compound] Cyclic compounds can be aliphatic if they are not aromatic.
[src:genetic-code/aliphatic-compound] Aliphatic compounds can be saturated, joined by single bonds (alkanes), or unsaturated, with double bonds (alkenes) or triple bonds (alkynes).
[src:genetic-code/aliphatic-compound] If other elements (heteroatoms) are bound to the carbon chain, the most common being oxygen, nitrogen, sulfur, and chlorine, it is no longer a hydrocarbon, and therefore no longer an aliphatic compound.
[src:genetic-code/aliphatic-compound] However, such compounds may still be referred to as aliphatic if the hydrocarbon portion of the molecule is aliphatic, e.g. aliphatic amines, to differentiate them from aromatic amines.
[src:genetic-code/aliphatic-compound] The least complex aliphatic compound is methane (CH4).
[src:genetic-code/allele] An **allele** is a variant of the sequence of nucleotides at a particular location, or locus, on a DNA molecule.
[src:genetic-code/allele] Alleles can differ at a single position through single-nucleotide polymorphisms, but they can also have insertions and deletions of up to several thousand base pairs.
[src:genetic-code/allele] Most alleles result in little or no change in the characteristics of an individual organism but sometimes different alleles can result in different observable phenotypic traits such as antibiotic resistance in bacteria, developmental mutations in fruit flies, and genetic diseases in humans.
[src:genetic-code/allele] Nearly all multicellular organisms have two sets of chromosomes at some point in their biological life cycle; that is, they are diploid.
[src:genetic-code/allele] For a given locus, if the two chromosomes contain the same allele, they, and the organism, are homozygous with respect to that allele.
[src:genetic-code/allele] If the alleles are different, they, and the organism, are heterozygous with respect to those alleles.
[src:genetic-code/allele] A notable example of this is Gregor Mendel's discovery that the white and purple flower colors in pea plants were the result of a single gene with two alleles.
[src:genetic-code/allele] Mendel's discovery of what are now known as alleles resulted in three laws that help understand how alleles are passed on to progeny.
[src:genetic-code/allele] Popular definitions of 'allele' typically refer only to different alleles within genes.
[src:genetic-code/allele] For example, the ABO blood grouping is controlled by the ABO gene, which has six common alleles (variants).
[src:genetic-code/allele] In population genetics, nearly every living human's phenotype for the ABO gene is some combination of just these six alleles.
[src:genetic-code/allele] It derives from the Greek prefix ἀλληλο-, *allelo-*, meaning "mutual", "reciprocal", or "each other", which itself is related to the Greek adjective ἄλλος, *allos* (cognate with Latin *alius*), meaning "other".
[src:genetic-code/allele] In many cases, genotypic interactions between the two alleles at a locus can be described as dominant or recessive, according to which of the two homozygous phenotypes the heterozygote most resembles.
[src:genetic-code/allele] Where the heterozygote is indistinguishable from one of the homozygotes, the allele expressed is the one that leads to the "dominant" phenotype, and the other allele is said to be "recessive".
[src:genetic-code/allele] In the case of a heterozygote, the dominant allele will mask the effect of the recessive allele, giving a dominant phenotype.
[src:genetic-code/allele] The phenotype of recessive alleles are observable when an organism is homozygous recessive for a gene.
[src:genetic-code/allele] The degree and pattern of dominance varies among loci.
[src:genetic-code/allele] This type of interaction was first formally-described by Gregor Mendel.
[src:genetic-code/allele] However, many traits defy this simple categorization and the phenotypes are modelled by co-dominance and polygenic inheritance.
[src:genetic-code/allele] The term "wild type" allele is sometimes used to describe an allele that is thought to contribute to the typical phenotypic character as seen in "wild" populations of organisms, such as fruit flies (*Drosophila melanogaster*).
[src:genetic-code/allele] Such a "wild type" allele was historically regarded as leading to a dominant (overpowering – always expressed), common, and normal phenotype, in contrast to "mutant" alleles that lead to recessive, rare, and frequently deleterious phenotypes.
[src:genetic-code/allele] It is now appreciated that most or all gene loci are highly polymorphic, with multiple alleles, whose frequencies vary from population to population, and that a great deal of genetic variation is hidden in the form of alleles that do not produce obvious phenotypic differences.
[src:genetic-code/allele] Wild type alleles are often denoted by a superscript plus sign (*i.e.*, *p+* for an allele *p*).
[src:genetic-code/allele] A population or species of organisms typically includes multiple alleles at each locus among various individuals.
[src:genetic-code/allele] Allelic variation at a locus is measurable as the number of alleles (polymorphism) present, or the proportion of heterozygotes in the population.
[src:genetic-code/allele] A null allele is a gene variant that lacks the gene's normal function because it either is not expressed, or the expressed protein is inactive.
[src:genetic-code/allele] For example, at the gene locus for the ABO blood type carbohydrate antigens in humans, classical genetics recognizes three alleles, IA, IB, and i, which determine compatibility of blood transfusions.
[src:genetic-code/allele] (It is now known that each of the A, B, and O alleles is actually a class of multiple alleles with different DNA sequences that produce proteins with identical properties: more than 70 alleles are known at the ABO locus.
[src:genetic-code/allele] The frequency of alleles in a diploid population can be used to predict the frequencies of the corresponding genotypes (see Hardy–Weinberg principle).
[src:genetic-code/allele] where *p* is the frequency of one allele and *q* is the frequency of the alternative allele, which necessarily sum to unity.
[src:genetic-code/allele] Then, *p*2 is the fraction of the population homozygous for the first allele, 2*pq* is the fraction of heterozygotes, and *q*2 is the fraction homozygous for the alternative allele.
[src:genetic-code/allele] If the first allele is dominant to the second then the fraction of the population that will show the dominant phenotype is *p*2 + 2*pq*, and the fraction with the recessive phenotype is *q*2.
[src:genetic-code/allele] A number of genetic disorders are caused when an individual inherits two recessive alleles for a single-gene trait.
[src:genetic-code/allele] Recessive genetic disorders include albinism, cystic fibrosis, galactosemia, phenylketonuria (PKU), and Tay–Sachs disease.
[src:genetic-code/allele] Other disorders are also due to recessive alleles, but because the gene locus is located on the X chromosome, so that males have only one copy (that is, they are hemizygous), they are more frequent in males than in females.
[src:genetic-code/allele] Examples include red–green color blindness and fragile X syndrome.
[src:genetic-code/allele] Other disorders, such as Huntington's disease, occur when an individual inherits only one dominant allele.
[src:genetic-code/allele] While heritable traits are typically studied in terms of genetic alleles, epigenetic marks such as DNA methylation can be inherited at specific genomic regions in certain species, a process termed transgenerational epigenetic inheritance.
[src:genetic-code/allele] The term *epiallele* is used to distinguish these heritable marks from traditional alleles, which are defined by nucleotide sequence.
[src:genetic-code/allele] A specific class of epiallele, the metastable epialleles, has been discovered in mice and in humans which is characterized by stochastic (probabilistic) establishment of epigenetic state that can be mitotically inherited.
[src:genetic-code/allele] The term "idiomorph", from Greek 'morphos' (form) and 'idio' (singular, unique), was introduced in 1990 in place of "allele" to denote sequences at the same locus in different strains that have no sequence similarity and probably do not share a common phylogenetic relationship.
[src:genetic-code/allele] It is used mainly in the genetic research of mycology.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Biologically relevant alternative splicing occurs as a normal phenomenon in eukaryotes, where it increases the number of proteins that can be encoded by the genome.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Alternative splicing was first observed in 1977.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The adenovirus produces five primary transcripts early in its infectious cycle, prior to viral DNA replication, and an additional one later, after DNA replication begins.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The early primary transcripts continue to be produced after DNA replication begins.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The additional primary transcript produced late in infection is large and comes from 5/6 of the 32kb adenovirus genome.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] This is much larger than any of the individual adenovirus mRNAs present in infected cells.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Researchers found that the primary RNA transcript produced by adenovirus type 2 in the late phase was spliced in many different ways, resulting in mRNAs encoding different viral proteins.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] In addition, the primary transcript contained multiple polyadenylation sites, giving different 3' ends for the processed mRNAs.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] In 1981, the first example of alternative splicing in a transcript from a normal, endogenous gene was characterized.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The gene encoding the thyroid hormone calcitonin was found to be alternatively spliced in mammalian cells.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The primary transcript from this gene contains 6 exons; the calcitonin mRNA contains exons 1–4, and terminates after a polyadenylation site in exon 4.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Another mRNA is produced from this pre-mRNA by skipping exon 4, and includes exons 1–3, 5, and 6.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] It encodes a protein known as CGRP (calcitonin gene related peptide).
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Examples of alternative splicing in immunoglobulin gene transcripts in mammals were also observed in the early 1980s.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Since then, many other examples of biologically relevant alternative splicing have been found in eukaryotes.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The "record-holder" for alternative splicing is a *D. melanogaster* gene called Dscam, which could potentially have 38,016 splice variants.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] In 2021, it was discovered that the genome of adenovirus type 2, the adenovirus in which alternative splicing was first identified, was able to produce a much greater variety of splice variants than previously thought.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] By using next generation sequencing technology, researchers were able to update the human adenovirus type 2 transcriptome and document the presence of 904 splice variants produced by the virus through a complex pattern of alternative splicing.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Very few of these splice variants have been shown to be functional, a point that the authors raise in their paper.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Five basic modes of alternative splicing are generally recognized.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] In addition to these primary modes of alternative splicing, there are two other main mechanisms by which different mRNAs may be generated from the same gene; multiple promoters and multiple polyadenylation sites.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Use of multiple promoters is properly described as a transcriptional regulation mechanism rather than alternative splicing; by starting transcription at different points, transcripts with different 5'-most exons can be generated.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] At the other end, multiple polyadenylation sites provide different 3' end points for the transcript.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Both of these mechanisms are found in combination with alternative splicing and provide additional variety in mRNAs derived from a gene.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] These modes describe basic splicing mechanisms, but may be inadequate to describe complex splicing events.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] For instance, the figure to the right shows three spliceforms from the mouse hyaluronidase 3 gene.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Comparing the exonic structure shown in the first line (green) with the one in the second line (yellow) shows intron retention, whereas the comparison between the second and the third spliceform (yellow vs. blue) exhibits exon skipping.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] A model nomenclature to uniquely designate all possible splicing patterns has recently been proposed.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] When the pre-mRNA has been transcribed from the DNA, it includes several introns and exons.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] (In nematodes, the mean is 4–5 exons and introns; in the fruit fly *Drosophila* there can be more than 100 introns and exons in one transcribed pre-mRNA.) The exons to be retained in the mRNA are determined during the splicing process.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The regulation and selection of splice sites are done by trans-acting splicing activator and splicing repressor proteins as well as cis-acting elements within the pre-mRNA itself such as exonic splicing enhancers and exonic splicing silencers.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The typical eukaryotic nuclear intron has consensus sequences defining important regions.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Each intron has the sequence GU at its 5' end.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The nucleotide at the branchpoint is always an A; the consensus around this sequence varies somewhat.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] In humans the branch site consensus sequence is yUnAy.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The branch site is followed by a series of pyrimidines – the polypyrimidine tract – then by AG at the 3' end.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Splicing of mRNA is performed by an RNA and protein complex known as the spliceosome, containing snRNPs designated U1, U2, U4, U5, and U6 (U3 is not involved in mRNA splicing).
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] U1 binds to the 5' GU and U2, with the assistance of the U2AF protein factors, binds to the branchpoint A within the branch site.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The complex at this stage is known as the spliceosome A complex.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Formation of the A complex is usually the key step in determining the ends of the intron to be spliced out, and defining the ends of the exon to be retained.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] (The U nomenclature derives from their high uridine content).
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The U4,U5,U6 complex binds, and U6 replaces the U1 position.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The remaining complex then performs two transesterification reactions.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] In the first transesterification, 5' end of the intron is cleaved from the upstream exon and joined to the branch site A by a 2',5'-phosphodiester linkage.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] In the second transesterification, the 3' end of the intron is cleaved from the downstream exon, and the two exons are joined by a phosphodiester bond.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The intron is then released in lariat form and degraded.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Splicing is regulated by trans-acting proteins (repressors and activators) and corresponding cis-acting regulatory sites (silencers and enhancers) on the pre-mRNA.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] However, as part of the complexity of alternative splicing, it is noted that the effects of a splicing factor are frequently position-dependent.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] That is, a splicing factor that serves as a splicing activator when bound to an intronic enhancer element may serve as a repressor when bound to its splicing element in the context of an exon, and vice versa.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The secondary structure of the pre-mRNA transcript also plays a role in regulating splicing, such as by bringing together splicing elements or by masking a sequence that would otherwise serve as a binding element for a splicing factor.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Together, these elements form a "splicing code" that governs how splicing will occur under different cellular conditions.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] There are two major types of cis-acting RNA sequence elements present in pre-mRNAs and they have corresponding trans-acting RNA-binding proteins.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Splicing *silencers* are sites to which splicing repressor proteins bind, reducing the probability that a nearby site will be used as a splice junction.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] These can be located in the intron itself (intronic splicing silencers, ISS) or in a neighboring exon (exonic splicing silencers, ESS).
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] They vary in sequence, as well as in the types of proteins that bind to them.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The majority of splicing repressors are heterogeneous nuclear ribonucleoproteins (hnRNPs) such as hnRNPA1 and polypyrimidine tract-binding protein (PTB).
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Splicing *enhancers* are sites to which splicing activator proteins bind, increasing the probability that a nearby site will be used as a splice junction.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] These also may occur in the intron (intronic splicing enhancers, ISE) or exon (exonic splicing enhancers, ESE).
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Most of the activator proteins that bind to ISEs and ESEs are members of the SR protein family.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Such proteins contain RNA recognition motifs and arginine and serine-rich (RS) domains.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] In general, the determinants of splicing work in an inter-dependent manner that depends on context, so that the rules governing how splicing is regulated form a splicing code.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The presence of a particular cis-acting RNA sequence element may increase the probability that a nearby site will be spliced in some cases, but decrease the probability in other cases, depending on context.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The context within which regulatory elements act includes cis-acting context that is established by the presence of other RNA sequence features, and trans-acting context that is established by cellular conditions.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] For example, some cis-acting RNA sequence elements influence splicing only if multiple elements are present in the same region so as to establish context.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] As another example, a cis-acting element can have opposite effects on splicing, depending on which proteins are expressed in the cell (e.g., neuronal versus non-neuronal PTB).
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The adaptive significance of splicing silencers and enhancers is attested by studies showing that there is strong selection in human genes against mutations that produce new silencers or disrupt existing enhancers.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Pre-mRNAs from the *Drosophila melanogaster* gene *dsx* contain 6 exons.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] In males, exons 1, 2, 3, 5, and 6 are joined to form the mRNA, which encodes a transcriptional regulatory protein required for male development.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] In females, exons 1, 2, 3, and 4 are joined, and a polyadenylation signal in exon 4 causes cleavage of the mRNA at that point.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The resulting mRNA is a transcriptional regulatory protein required for female development.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The intron upstream from exon 4 has a polypyrimidine tract that does not match the consensus sequence well, so that U2AF proteins bind poorly to it without assistance from splicing activators.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] This 3' splice acceptor site is therefore not used in males.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Females, however, produce the splicing activator Transformer (Tra) (see below).
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The SR protein Tra2 is produced in both sexes and binds to an ESE in exon 4; if Tra is present, it binds to Tra2 and, along with another SR protein, forms a complex that assists U2AF proteins in binding to the weak polypyrimidine tract.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] U2 is recruited to the associated branchpoint, and this leads to inclusion of exon 4 in the mRNA.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Pre-mRNAs of the *Transformer* (Tra) gene of *Drosophila melanogaster* undergo alternative splicing via the alternative acceptor site mode.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The gene Tra encodes a protein that is expressed only in females.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The primary transcript of this gene contains an intron with two possible acceptor sites.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] In males, the upstream acceptor site is used.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] This causes a longer version of exon 2 to be included in the processed transcript, including an early stop codon.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The resulting mRNA encodes a truncated protein product that is inactive.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Females produce the master sex determination protein Sex lethal (Sxl).
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The Sxl protein is a splicing repressor that binds to an ISS in the RNA of the Tra transcript near the upstream acceptor site, preventing U2AF protein from binding to the polypyrimidine tract.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] This prevents the use of this junction, shifting the spliceosome binding to the downstream acceptor site.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Splicing at this point bypasses the stop codon, which is excised as part of the intron.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The resulting mRNA encodes an active Tra protein, which itself is a regulator of alternative splicing of other sex-related genes (see *dsx* above).
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Multiple isoforms of the Fas receptor protein are produced by alternative splicing.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Two normally occurring isoforms in humans are produced by an exon-skipping mechanism.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] An mRNA including exon 6 encodes the membrane-bound form of the Fas receptor, which promotes apoptosis, or programmed cell death.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Increased expression of Fas receptor in skin cells chronically exposed to the sun, and absence of expression in skin cancer cells, suggests that this mechanism may be important in elimination of pre-cancerous cells in humans.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] If exon 6 is skipped, the resulting mRNA encodes a soluble Fas protein that does not promote apoptosis.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The inclusion or skipping of the exon depends on two antagonistic proteins, TIA-1 and polypyrimidine tract-binding protein (PTB).
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] This mechanism is an example of exon definition in splicing.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] A spliceosome assembles on an intron, and the snRNP subunits fold the RNA so that the 5' and 3' ends of the intron are joined.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] However, recently studied examples such as this one show that there are also interactions between the ends of the exon.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] In this particular case, these exon definition interactions are necessary to allow the binding of core splicing factors prior to assembly of the spliceosomes on the two flanking introns.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] HIV, the retrovirus that causes AIDS in humans, produces a single primary RNA transcript, which is alternatively spliced in multiple ways to produce over 40 different mRNAs.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Equilibrium among differentially spliced transcripts provides multiple mRNAs encoding different products that are required for viral multiplication.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] One of the differentially spliced transcripts contains the *tat* gene, in which exon 2 is a cassette exon that may be skipped or included.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The inclusion of tat exon 2 in the RNA is regulated by competition between the splicing repressor hnRNP A1 and the SR protein SC35.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Within exon 2 an exonic splicing silencer sequence (ESS) and an exonic splicing enhancer sequence (ESE) overlap.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] If A1 repressor protein binds to the ESS, it initiates cooperative binding of multiple A1 molecules, extending into the 5' donor site upstream of exon 2 and preventing the binding of the core splicing factor U2AF35 to the polypyrimidine tract.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] If SC35 binds to the ESE, it prevents A1 binding and maintains the 5' donor site in an accessible state for assembly of the spliceosome.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Competition between the activator and repressor ensures that both mRNA types (with and without exon 2) are produced.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Genuine alternative splicing occurs in both protein-coding genes and non-coding genes to produce multiple products (proteins or non-coding RNAs).
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] External information is needed in order to decide which product is made, given a DNA sequence and the initial transcript.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Since the methods of regulation are inherited, this provides novel ways for mutations to affect gene expression.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Alternative splicing may provide evolutionary flexibility.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] A single point mutation may cause a given exon to be occasionally excluded or included from a transcript during splicing, allowing production of a new protein isoform without loss of the original protein.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Studies have identified intrinsically disordered regions (see Intrinsically unstructured proteins) as enriched in the non-constitutive exons suggesting that protein isoforms may display functional diversity due to the alteration of functional modules within these regions.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Such functional diversity achieved by isoforms is reflected by their expression patterns and can be predicted by machine learning approaches.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Comparative studies indicate that alternative splicing preceded multicellularity in evolution, and suggest that this mechanism might have been co-opted to assist in the development of multicellular organisms.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Research based on the Human Genome Project and other genome sequencing has shown that humans have only about 30% more genes than the roundworm *Caenorhabditis elegans*, and only about twice as many as the fly *Drosophila melanogaster*.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] This finding led to speculation that the perceived greater complexity of humans, or vertebrates generally, might be due to higher rates of alternative splicing in humans than are found in invertebrates.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Another study, however, proposed that these results were an artifact of the different numbers of ESTs available for the various organisms.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] When they compared alternative splicing frequencies in random subsets of genes from each organism, the authors concluded that vertebrates do have higher rates of alternative splicing than invertebrates.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Changes in the RNA processing machinery may lead to mis-splicing of multiple transcripts, while single-nucleotide alterations in splice sites or cis-acting splicing regulatory sites may lead to differences in splicing of a single gene, and thus in the mRNA produced from a mutant gene's transcripts.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] A study in 2005 involving probabilistic analyses indicated that greater than 60% of human disease-causing mutations affect splicing rather than directly affecting coding sequences.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] A more recent study indicates that one-third of all hereditary diseases are likely to have a splicing component.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Regardless of exact percentage, a number of splicing-related diseases do exist.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] As described below, a prominent example of splicing-related diseases is cancer.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Abnormally spliced mRNAs are also found in a high proportion of cancerous cells.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Combined RNA-Seq and proteomics analyses have revealed striking differential expression of splice isoforms of key proteins in important cancer pathways.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] It is not always clear whether such aberrant patterns of splicing contribute to the cancerous growth, or are merely consequence of cellular abnormalities associated with cancer.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] For certain types of cancer, like in colorectal and prostate, the number of splicing errors per cancer has been shown to vary greatly between individual cancers, a phenomenon referred to as transcriptome instability.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Transcriptome instability has further been shown to correlate greatly with reduced expression level of splicing factor genes.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Mutation of *DNMT3A* has been demonstrated to contribute to hematologic malignancies, and that *DNMT3A*-mutated cell lines exhibit transcriptome instability as compared to their isogenic wildtype counterparts.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] In fact, there is actually a reduction of alternative splicing in cancerous cells compared to normal ones, and the types of splicing differ; for instance, cancerous cells show higher levels of intron retention than normal cells, but lower levels of exon skipping.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Some of the differences in splicing in cancerous cells may be due to the high frequency of somatic mutations in splicing factor genes, and some may result from changes in phosphorylation of trans-acting splicing factors.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Others may be produced by changes in the relative amounts of splicing factors produced; for instance, breast cancer cells have been shown to have increased levels of the splicing factor SF2/ASF.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] One study found that a relatively small percentage (383 out of over 26000) of alternative splicing variants were significantly higher in frequency in tumor cells than normal cells, suggesting that there is a limited set of genes which, when mis-spliced, contribute to tumor development.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] It is believed however that the deleterious effects of mis-spliced transcripts are usually safeguarded and eliminated by a cellular posttranscriptional quality control mechanism termed nonsense-mediated mRNA decay [NMD].
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] One example of a specific splicing variant associated with cancers is in one of the human DNMT genes.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Three DNMT genes encode enzymes that add methyl groups to DNA, a modification that often has regulatory effects.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Several abnormally spliced DNMT3B mRNAs are found in tumors and cancer cell lines.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] In two separate studies, expression of two of these abnormally spliced mRNAs in mammalian cells caused changes in the DNA methylation patterns in those cells.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Cells with one of the abnormal mRNAs also grew twice as fast as control cells, indicating a direct contribution to tumor development by this product.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Another example is the *Ron* (*MST1R*) proto-oncogene.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] An important property of cancerous cells is their ability to move and invade normal tissue.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Production of an abnormally spliced transcript of *Ron* has been found to be associated with increased levels of the SF2/ASF in breast cancer cells.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The abnormal isoform of the Ron protein encoded by this mRNA leads to cell motility.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Overexpression of a truncated splice variant of the FOSB gene – ΔFosB – in a specific population of neurons in the nucleus accumbens has been identified as the causal mechanism involved in the induction and maintenance of an addiction to drugs and natural rewards.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Recent provocative studies point to a key function of chromatin structure and histone modifications in alternative splicing regulation.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] These insights suggest that epigenetic regulation determines not only what parts of the genome are expressed but also how they are spliced.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Transcriptome-wide analysis of alternative splicing is typically performed by high-throughput RNA-sequencing.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Most commonly, by short-read sequencing, such as by Illumina instrumentation.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] But even more informative, by long-read sequencing, such as by Nanopore or PacBio instrumentation.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Transcriptome-wide analyses can for example be used to measure the amount of deviating alternative splicing, such as in a cancer cohort.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Deep sequencing technologies have been used to conduct genome-wide analyses of both unprocessed and processed mRNAs; thus providing insights into alternative splicing.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] For example, results from use of deep sequencing indicate that, in humans, an estimated 95% of transcripts from multiexon genes undergo alternative splicing, with a number of pre-mRNA transcripts spliced in a tissue-specific manner.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Functional genomics and computational approaches based on multiple instance learning have also been developed to integrate RNA-seq data to predict functions for alternatively spliced isoforms.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Deep sequencing has also aided in the *in vivo* detection of the transient lariats that are released during splicing, the determination of branch site sequences, and the large-scale mapping of branchpoints in human pre-mRNA transcripts.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] More historically, alternatively spliced transcripts have been found by comparing EST sequences, but this requires sequencing of very large numbers of ESTs.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Most EST libraries come from a very limited number of tissues, so tissue-specific splice variants are likely to be missed in any case.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] High-throughput approaches to investigate splicing have, however, been developed, such as: DNA microarray–based analyses, RNA-binding assays, and deep sequencing.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] These methods can be used to screen for polymorphisms or mutations in or around splicing elements that affect protein binding.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] When combined with splicing assays, including *in vivo* reporter gene assays, the functional effects of polymorphisms or mutations on the splicing of pre-mRNA transcripts can then be analyzed.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] In microarray analysis, arrays of DNA fragments representing individual exons (*e.g.* Affymetrix exon microarray) or exon/exon boundaries (*e.g.* arrays from ExonHit or Jivan) have been used.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The array is then probed with labeled cDNA from tissues of interest.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] The probe cDNAs bind to DNA from the exons that are included in mRNAs in their tissue of origin, or to DNA from the boundary where two exons have been joined.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] This can reveal the presence of particular alternatively spliced mRNAs.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] CLIP (Cross-linking and immunoprecipitation) uses UV radiation to link proteins to RNA molecules in a tissue during splicing.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] A trans-acting splicing regulatory protein of interest is then precipitated using specific antibodies.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] When the RNA attached to that protein is isolated and cloned, it reveals the target sequences for that protein.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Use of the MEGAshift method has provided insights into the regulation of alternative splicing by allowing for the identification of sequences in pre-mRNA transcripts surrounding alternatively spliced exons that mediate binding to different splicing factors, such as ASF/SF2 and PTB.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] This approach has also been used to aid in determining the relationship between RNA secondary structure and the binding of splicing factors.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Use of reporter assays makes it possible to find the splicing proteins involved in a specific alternative splicing event by constructing reporter genes that will express one of two different fluorescent proteins depending on the splicing reaction that occurs.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] This method has been used to isolate mutants affecting splicing and thus to identify novel splicing regulatory proteins inactivated in those mutants.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] Recent advancements in protein structure prediction have facilitated the development of new tools for genome annotation and alternative splicing analysis.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] For instance, isoform.io, a platform guided by protein structure predictions, has evaluated hundreds of thousands of isoforms of human protein-coding genes assembled from numerous RNA sequencing experiments across a variety of human tissues.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] This comprehensive analysis has led to the identification of numerous isoforms with more confidently predicted structure and potentially superior function compared to canonical isoforms in the latest human gene database.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] By integrating structural predictions with expression and evolutionary evidence, this approach has demonstrated the potential of protein structure prediction as a tool for refining the annotation of the human genome.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] There is a collection of alternative splicing databases.
[src:genetic-code/alternative-splicing] These databases are useful for finding genes having pre-mRNAs undergoing alternative splicing and alternative splicing events or to study the functional impact of alternative splicing.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] The codons specify which amino acid will be added next during protein biosynthesis.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] With some exceptions, a three-nucleotide codon in a nucleic acid sequence specifies a single amino acid.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] The vast majority of genes are encoded with a single scheme (see the RNA codon table).
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] That scheme is often called the canonical or standard genetic code, or simply *the* genetic code, though variant codes (such as in mitochondria) exist.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Efforts to understand how proteins are encoded began after DNA's structure was discovered in 1953.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] The key discoverers, English biophysicist Francis Crick and American biologist James Watson, working together at the Cavendish Laboratory of the University of Cambridge, hypothesised that information flows from DNA and that there is a link between DNA and proteins.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Soviet-American physicist George Gamow was the first to give a workable scheme for protein synthesis from DNA.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] He postulated that sets of three bases (triplets) must be employed to encode the 20 standard amino acids used by living cells to build proteins, which would allow a maximum of 43 = 64 amino acids (all permutations of the four bases, read three at a time).
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] He named this DNA–protein interaction (the original genetic code) as the "diamond code".
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] In 1954, Gamow created an informal scientific organisation the RNA Tie Club, as suggested by Watson, for scientists of different persuasions who were interested in how proteins were synthesised from genes.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] However, the club could have only 20 permanent members to represent each of the 20 amino acids; and four additional honorary members to represent the four nucleotides of DNA.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] The first scientific contribution of the club, later recorded as "one of the most important unpublished articles in the history of science" and "the most famous unpublished paper in the annals of molecular biology", was made by Crick.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Crick presented a type-written paper titled "On Degenerate Templates and the Adaptor Hypothesis: A Note for the RNA Tie Club" to the members of the club in January 1955, which "totally changed the way we thought about protein synthesis", as Watson recalled.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] The hypothesis states that the triplet code was not passed on to amino acids as Gamow thought, but carried by a different molecule, an adaptor, that interacts with amino acids.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] The adaptor was later identified as tRNA.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] The Crick, Brenner, Barnett and Watts-Tobin experiment first demonstrated that **codons** consist of three DNA bases.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Heinrich Matthaei were the first to reveal the nature of a codon in 1961.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] They used a cell-free system to translate a poly-uracil RNA sequence (i.e., UUUUU...) and discovered that the polypeptide that they had synthesized consisted of only the amino acid phenylalanine.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] They thereby deduced that the codon UUU specified the amino acid phenylalanine.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] This was followed by experiments in Severo Ochoa's laboratory that demonstrated that the poly-adenine RNA sequence (AAAAA...) coded for the polypeptide poly-lysine and that the poly-cytosine RNA sequence (CCCCC...) coded for the polypeptide poly-proline.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Therefore, the codon AAA specified the amino acid lysine, and the codon CCC specified the amino acid proline.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Using various copolymers most of the remaining codons were then determined.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Subsequent work by Har Gobind Khorana identified the rest of the genetic code.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Holley determined the structure of transfer RNA (tRNA), the adapter molecule that facilitates the process of translating RNA into protein.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] This work was based upon Ochoa's earlier studies, yielding the latter the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1959 for work on the enzymology of RNA synthesis.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Extending this work, Nirenberg and Philip Leder revealed the code's triplet nature and deciphered its codons.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] In these experiments, various combinations of mRNA were passed through a filter that contained ribosomes, the components of cells that translate RNA into protein.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Unique triplets promoted the binding of specific tRNAs to the ribosome.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Leder and Nirenberg were able to determine the sequences of 54 out of 64 codons in their experiments.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Khorana, Holley and Nirenberg received the Nobel Prize (1968) for their work.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] The three stop codons were named by discoverers Richard Epstein and Charles Steinberg.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] "Amber" was named after their friend Harris Bernstein, whose last name means "amber" in German.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] The other two stop codons were named "ochre" and "opal" in order to keep the "color names" theme.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] In a broad academic audience, the concept of the evolution of the genetic code from the original and ambiguous genetic code to a well-defined ("frozen") code with the repertoire of 20 (+2) canonical amino acids is widely accepted.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] However, there are different opinions, concepts, approaches and ideas, which is the best way to change it experimentally.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Even models are proposed that predict "entry points" for synthetic amino acid invasion of the genetic code.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Sisido extended some codons to have four and five bases.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Benner constructed a functional 65th (*in vivo*) codon.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Söll and co-workers reported the full substitution of all 20,899 tryptophan residues (UGG codons) with unnatural thienopyrrole-alanine in the genetic code of the bacterium *E. coli*.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] In 2016 the first stable semisynthetic organism was created.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] It was a (single cell) bacterium with two synthetic bases (called X and Y).
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] In 2017, researchers in South Korea reported that they had engineered a mouse with an extended genetic code that can produce proteins with unnatural amino acids.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] In May 2019, researchers reported the creation of a new "Syn61" strain of the *E. coli* bacteria.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] This strain has a fully synthetic genome that is refactored (all overlaps expanded), recoded (removing the use of three out of 64 codons completely), and further modified to remove the now unnecessary tRNAs and release factors.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] It is fully viable and grows 1.6× slower than its wild-type counterpart "MDS42".
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] In 2025, researchers reported a new "Syn57" strain, which removes the use of 7 out of 64 codons completely.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] A reading frame is defined by the initial triplet of nucleotides from which translation starts.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] It sets the frame for a run of successive, non-overlapping codons, which is known as an "open reading frame" (ORF).
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] For example, the string 5'-AAATGAACG-3' (see figure), if read from the first position, contains the codons AAA, TGA, and ACG ; if read from the second position, it contains the codons AAT and GAA ; and if read from the third position, it contains the codons ATG and AAC.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Every sequence can, thus, be read in its 5' → 3' direction in three reading frames, each producing a possibly distinct amino acid sequence: in the given example, Lys (K)-Trp (W)-Thr (T), Asn (N)-Glu (E), or Met (M)-Asn (N), respectively (when translating with the vertebrate mitochondrial code).
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] When DNA is double-stranded, six possible reading frames are defined, three in the forward orientation on one strand and three reverse on the opposite strand.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Protein-coding frames are defined by a start codon, usually the first AUG codon in the RNA, (ATG in DNA) sequence.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] In eukaryotes, open reading frames in exons are often interrupted by introns.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Translation starts with a chain-initiation codon or start codon.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] The start codon alone is not sufficient to begin the process.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Nearby sequences such as the Shine-Dalgarno sequence in *E. coli* and initiation factors are also required to start translation.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] The most common start codon is AUG, which is read as methionine or as formylmethionine (in bacteria, mitochondria, and plastids).
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Alternative start codons depending on the organism include "GUG" or "UUG"; these codons normally represent valine and leucine, respectively, but as start codons they are translated as methionine or formylmethionine.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] The three stop codons have names: UAG is *amber*, UGA is *opal* (sometimes also called *umber*), and UAA is *ochre*.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Stop codons are also called "termination" or "nonsense" codons.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] They signal release of the nascent polypeptide from the ribosome because no cognate tRNA has anticodons complementary to these stop signals, allowing a release factor to bind to the ribosome instead.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] During the process of DNA replication, errors occasionally occur in the polymerization of the second strand.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] These errors, mutations, can affect an organism's phenotype, especially if they occur within the protein coding sequence of a gene.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Error rates are typically 1 error in every 10–100 million bases—due to the "proofreading" ability of DNA polymerases.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Missense mutations and nonsense mutations are examples of point mutations that can cause genetic diseases such as sickle-cell disease and thalassemia respectively.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Clinically important missense mutations generally change the properties of the coded amino acid residue among basic, acidic, polar or non-polar states, whereas nonsense mutations result in a stop codon.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Mutations that disrupt the reading frame sequence by indels (insertions or deletions) of a non-multiple of 3 nucleotide bases are known as frameshift mutations.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] These mutations usually result in a completely different translation from the original, and likely cause a stop codon to be read, which truncates the protein.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] These mutations may impair the protein's function and are thus rare in *in vivo* protein-coding sequences.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] One reason inheritance of frameshift mutations is rare is that, if the protein being translated is essential for growth under the selective pressures the organism faces, absence of a functional protein may cause death before the organism becomes viable.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Frameshift mutations may result in severe genetic diseases such as Tay–Sachs disease.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Although most mutations that change protein sequences are harmful or neutral, some mutations have benefits.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] These mutations may enable the mutant organism to withstand particular environmental stresses better than wild type organisms, or reproduce more quickly.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] In these cases a mutation will tend to become more common in a population through natural selection.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Viruses that use RNA as their genetic material have rapid mutation rates, which can be an advantage, since these viruses thereby evolve rapidly, and thus evade the immune system defensive responses.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] In large populations of asexually reproducing organisms, for example, *E. coli*, multiple beneficial mutations may co-occur.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] This phenomenon is called clonal interference and causes competition among the mutations.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Degeneracy is the redundancy of the genetic code.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] This term was given by Bernfield and Nirenberg.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] The genetic code has redundancy but no ambiguity (see the codon tables below for the full correlation).
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] For example, although codons GAA and GAG both specify glutamic acid (redundancy), neither specifies another amino acid (no ambiguity).
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] The codons encoding one amino acid may differ in any of their three positions.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] NCN yields amino acid residues that are small in size and moderate in hydropathicity; NAN encodes average size hydrophilic residues.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Nevertheless, changes in the first position of the codons are more important than changes in the second position on a global scale.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] The reason may be that charge reversal (from a positive to a negative charge or vice versa) can only occur upon mutations in the first position of certain codons, but not upon changes in the second position of any codon.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Such charge reversal may have dramatic consequences for the structure or function of a protein.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] This aspect may have been largely underestimated by previous studies.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] The frequency of codons, also known as codon usage bias, can vary from species to species with functional implications for the control of translation.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] The codon varies by organism; for example, most common proline codon in E. coli is CCG, whereas in humans this is the least used proline codon.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] In some proteins, non-standard amino acids are substituted for standard stop codons, depending on associated signal sequences in the messenger RNA.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] For example, UGA can code for selenocysteine and UAG can code for pyrrolysine.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Selenocysteine came to be seen as the 21st amino acid, and pyrrolysine as the 22nd.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Both selenocysteine and pyrrolysine may be present in the same organism.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Although the genetic code is normally fixed in an organism, the achaeal prokaryote *Acetohalobium arabaticum* can expand its genetic code from 20 to 21 amino acids (by including pyrrolysine) under different conditions of growth.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] There was originally a simple and widely accepted argument that the genetic code should be universal: namely, that any variation in the genetic code would be lethal to the organism (although Crick had stated that viruses were an exception).
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] This is known as the "frozen accident" argument for the universality of the genetic code.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] However, in his seminal paper on the origins of the genetic code in 1968, Francis Crick still stated that the universality of the genetic code in all organisms was an unproven assumption, and was probably not true in some instances.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] He predicted that "The code is universal (the same in all organisms) or nearly so".
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] The first variation was discovered in 1979, by researchers studying human mitochondrial genes.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Many slight variants were discovered thereafter, including various alternative mitochondrial codes.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] These minor variants for example involve translation of the codon UGA as tryptophan in *Mycoplasma* species, and translation of CUG as a serine rather than leucine in yeasts of the "CTG clade" (such as *Candida albicans*).
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Because viruses must use the same genetic code as their hosts, modifications to the standard genetic code could interfere with viral protein synthesis or functioning.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] However, viruses such as totiviruses have adapted to the host's genetic code modification.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] In bacteria and archaea, GUG and UUG are common start codons.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] In rare cases, certain proteins may use alternative start codons.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] This type of recoding is induced by a high-readthrough stop codon context and it is referred to as *functional translational readthrough*.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Despite these differences, all known naturally occurring codes are very similar.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] The coding mechanism is the same for all organisms: three-base codons, tRNA, ribosomes, single direction reading and translating single codons into single amino acids.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] The most extreme variations occur in certain ciliates where the meaning of stop codons depends on their position within mRNA.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] When close to the 3' end they act as terminators while in internal positions they either code for amino acids as in *Condylostoma magnum* or trigger ribosomal frameshifting as in *Euplotes*.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] The origins and variation of the genetic code, including the mechanisms behind the evolvability of the genetic code, have been widely studied, and some studies have been done experimentally evolving the genetic code of some organisms.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Variant genetic codes used by an organism can be inferred by identifying highly conserved genes encoded in that genome, and comparing its codon usage to the amino acids in homologous proteins of other organisms.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] For example, the program FACIL infers a genetic code by searching which amino acids in homologous protein domains are most often aligned to every codon.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] The resulting amino acid (or stop codon) probabilities for each codon are displayed in a genetic code logo.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] As of January 2022, the most complete survey of genetic codes is done by Shulgina and Eddy, who screened 250,000 prokaryotic genomes using their Codetta tool.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] This tool uses a similar approach to FACIL with a larger Pfam database.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Despite the NCBI already providing 27 translation tables, the authors were able to find new 5 genetic code variations (corroborated by tRNA mutations) and correct several misattributions.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Codetta was later used to analyze genetic code change in ciliates.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] The genetic code is a key part of the history of life.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Under the RNA world hypothesis, self-replicating RNA molecules preceded significant use of proteins.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Under the nucleopeptide world hypothesis, significant use of peptides preceded the genetic code and was concurrent with early life's sophisticated use of RNA.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Transfer RNA molecules appear to have evolved before modern aminoacyl-tRNA synthetases.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] It is possible that synthetases replaced an earlier system of ribozymes (RNA enzymes), or that amino acids were recognized by unique pockets in the tertiary structure of proto-tRNAs.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] It is not known why the genetic code only uses L-amino acids and not D-amino acids.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Any evolutionary model for the code's origin must account for its robustness of encoded proteins to errors during DNA replication and during translation.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Many single nucleotide errors are synonymous, and those that are not tend to cause the substitution of a biochemically similar amino acid.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Even holding the structure of the code the same such that clusters of codons encode the same amino acid, which amino acids are encoded by which sets of codons is "one in a million" with respect to robustness.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Biochemically similar amino acids tend to share the same middle nucleotide, while synonymous changes generally happen at the third nucleotide.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Amino acids that share the same biosynthetic pathway tend to have the same first base in their codons.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] This could be an evolutionary relic of an early, simpler genetic code with fewer amino acids that later evolved to code a larger set of amino acids.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] It could also reflect steric and chemical properties that had another effect on the codon during its evolution.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Amino acids with similar physical properties also tend to have similar codons, reducing the problems caused by point mutations and mistranslations.
[src:genetic-code/genetic-code] Three main hypotheses address the origin of the genetic code.
